      <trans-unit id="11783" identifier="93f7f710b96d25060d8fc0fdd8426091">
        <source>Applying what we have just learnt</source>
        <target>crwdns11783:0crwdne11783:0</target>
        <note>Context: Headline 2&#13;
XPath: /h2[4]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="15597" identifier="7480a499f5470f24bc035d7364c2b6a8">
        <source>If any data is organised in order and a binary search is applied, then you can eliminate a lot of data quickly - cutting the number of items in half each time.</source>
        <target>crwdns15597:0crwdne15597:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[24]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="15598" identifier="32f83df1b7a8e6d38af7e1cec77bc50c">
        <source>As a slightly different example, if we were trying to guess a number between 1 and 1,000,000, then asking if the number is over 500,000 would eliminate 500,000 options in one question, the second question eliminates 250,000, the third question 125,000, and so on.</source>
        <target>crwdns15598:0crwdne15598:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[24]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="15599" identifier="bbdbf1f157028e115d38658baebd0513">
        <source>So in 3 questions you have eliminated 875,000 numbers.</source>
        <target>crwdns15599:0crwdne15599:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[24]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="15600" identifier="0cffb599b20eac5abd4eb6c16f1849f0">
        <source>With just 20 questions you can find the one number between 1 and 1,000,000.</source>
        <target>crwdns15600:0crwdne15600:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[24]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="15601" identifier="46ba65bb3d4401471ab1519796221095">
        <source>It's the same searching for objects that are sorted in descending order - each value that is checked halves the number of possible locations.</source>
        <target>crwdns15601:0crwdne15601:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[24]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="15602" identifier="8b48bb5b293b865732b4f32bd1fd1bad">
        <source>Dividing problems in half makes them very small very quickly.</source>
        <target>crwdns15602:0crwdne15602:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[24]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="15603" identifier="0484ec422c5496076bd51b4c08ae3438">
        <source>{image file-path=&quot;img/topics/divide.png&quot;}</source>
        <target>crwdns15603:0crwdne15603:0</target>
        <note>Context: Paragraph text&#13;
XPath: /p[25]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="15604" identifier="79898200356c2fd7736e15d0dc032bed">
        <source>This general process is called &quot;divide and conquer&quot; - you break the problem into (two) parts, and deal with each part separately, in turn break them into two parts.</source>
        <target>crwdns15604:0crwdne15604:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[26]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="15605" identifier="128ae6440becbe701f9f7fbdf5ae62c1">
        <source>Very soon you end up with very easy tasks, such as dealing with just one item.</source>
        <target>crwdns15605:0crwdne15605:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[26]</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="15606" identifier="533ffe3671287f78ade8188761c31b63">
        <source>It's a great strategy for reducing any big task or challenge to achievable goals!</source>
        <target>crwdns15606:0crwdne15606:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /p[26]</note>
      </trans-unit>
